<!-- HISTORY -->
<section class="history-section" id="history">
  <div class="history-accent-line"></div>
  <div class="history-inner">
    <div>
      <div class="eyebrow">Roots & Ruins</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">A Brief <span>History</span> of Gowanus</h2>
      <div class="history-intro">
        <p>In <strong>1636</strong>, Gowanus Bay — named after Gauwane, a Canarsee Indian leader — was the site of the first Dutch settlement in what is now Brooklyn. Early settlers harnessed the tidal creek to power their gristmills.</p>
        <p>During the <strong>American Revolutionary War</strong>, Gowanus was the site of the Battle of Brooklyn — one of the largest engagements of the entire war. There's even a playground nearby commemorating the battle.</p>
        <p>By the <strong>1860s</strong>, the creek had been dug into a full canal. Factories, oil refineries, and gas works flooded the banks — as did their waste, pumped directly into the water through combined sewers.</p>
        <p>In the <strong>1980s</strong>, the derelict 230 3rd Street — an old 19th-century munitions factory — became the massive <strong>Gowanus Memorial Artyard</strong>, one of the largest art installations of its era. The <strong>Coignet Stone Building</strong> next door (one of America's earliest concrete structures) still stands today.</p>
        <p>Artists kept coming. By the 1990s, Gowanus had quietly become one of Brooklyn's most vital creative communities — built from the ruins of industry, and the affordable spaces those ruins left behind.</p>
        <a href="https://gowanuslocal.substack.com/p/a-brief-history-of-gowanus" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-ghost" style="margin-top:1.75rem;display:inline-block;font-size:0.68rem;">Read the full history on Substack →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="history-timeline">
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1636</div>
        <p class="tl-text">Dutch farmers settle <strong>Gowanus Bay</strong>. Named for Gauwane, a Canarsee Indian leader. The tidal creek powers the first gristmills in Brooklyn.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1776</div>
        <p class="tl-text">The <strong>Battle of Brooklyn</strong> is fought across Gowanus — the largest battle of the Revolutionary War. The neighborhood is still marked by it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1860s</div>
        <p class="tl-text">The creek is engineered into a <strong>full industrial canal</strong>. Factories, gas works, and oil refineries move in. Combined sewers dump directly into the water.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1889</div>
        <p class="tl-text">The <strong>Carroll Street Bridge</strong> is built — the oldest retractile bridge in the United States. It still operates today, by hand, using the original mechanism.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1940s</div>
        <p class="tl-text">Post-WWII decline sets in. <strong>NYCHA housing</strong> is built to house returning veterans. Industry begins to leave the canal behind.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">1980s–90s</div>
        <p class="tl-text">The <strong>Gowanus Memorial Artyard</strong> opens at 230 3rd St. Artists move into cheap warehouse lofts. The creative community that defines Gowanus today quietly takes root.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">2010</div>
        <p class="tl-text">The EPA designates the canal a <strong>Superfund site</strong>. Cleanup begins in 2020. The <a href="https://gowanuscanalconservancy.org/superfund/" target="_blank">Gowanus Canal Conservancy</a> tracks every step and advocates hard for the community.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">2012</div>
        <p class="tl-text"><strong>Powerhouse Arts</strong> buys "The Bat Cave" — a derelict BRT power station. It opens in 2022 as a world-class arts fabrication nonprofit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tl-item">
        <div class="tl-year">2021</div>
        <p class="tl-text">An <strong>82-block rezoning</strong> is approved, triggering the largest wave of development Gowanus has ever seen. The <a href="https://gowanusimprovementdistrict.org/" target="_blank">Gowanus Improvement District</a> forms to keep the neighborhood's soul intact.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

